We have two points:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
(4, -12) \qquad (a, a^2-6a)
\end{align*}

So the slope, \emph{m}, of the line going through these two points is
the ratio of rise (change in the y-coordinates) over run (change in the
x-coordinates):

\begin{align*}
m = \frac{(-12) - (a^2-6a)}{4-a} = -\frac{a^2-6a+12}{4-a}
\end{align*}
